		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			<br><blockquote><hr>KAhm wrote:<br><DIV>The problem with factoring in Defensive like that is that the mobs in single group content rarely, if ever, last 3 minutes. This creates a somewhat inaccurate picture as unless the tank is facing the mobs in rapid order, (up to 6 if the fights are 30 seconds each), with no gap between contact, they will not get the full use of Defensive.</DIV><DIV> </DIV><DIV>I really have some serrious doubts as to the accuracy of including such Disciplines into the equation, it's clear these were not designed for today's single group content or else they would have a more compatible duration and refresh.</DIV><DIV> </DIV><DIV><u>Which leads to a question to ask Warriors, do they use these Discs in this manner, popping Defensive and Evasive when they refresh?</u> Which is also a huge factor to consider when making such comparisons otherwise your just pen and paper theory that doesn't actually apply to the game.</DIV><br><hr></blockquote><br><br><br>The most I have used Defensive and Evasive throughout most of my gameplay with it (5yrs) is on raid mobs or last option save in a group. And thats it ... the ghost of Furor should linger around saying "i told you so" about those defensive disciplines being a crutch and should have been innate higher mitigation/avoidance as the character grew in power.<br><br>In GoD and some instances of PoP and Luclin, you could argue that warriors Defensive was scaled to cutting-edge groups in order to progress, and in the GoD expansion just got a little TOO HARD for all but the usual WAR/CLR/ENC set ups. But now either some people are not paying attention on the going ons of the content and classes tweaking that it seems laughable to even point out the obvious: content dropped to a monk tanking level means WAR discipline toolset is now pushed even higher up to RAID mode then before, where it makes NO SENSE to have them if you are just grouping and knights asking for tanking better vs THAT kind of content? ... and on top of that devs forgot you guys use a spellbook (don't argue about stuns/snares ... you got MORE than that in there), gets boosted a tad (higher dmg, heals, shorter recycle time .. level spread spells? c'mon!)<br><br>Practical common sense: When you are in group mode, you are either A) XP grinding  or B) Loot farming, and you want to do it in the most efficient way possible. You NEVER bring a Warrior for 98.99% of the content that is out there, UNLESS its a name and more than likely requires MORE than 6 people. And usually thats how it's panning out to being.<br><br>The dilemma isn't one created by warrior or knights ... its the devs that have no clue on how to do checks and balances to those classes.<br><br>If you want to keep the status quo then Warrior will need to get mitigation/avoidance and DPS boosted to where it will matter to a group and make them desirable because of less dmg intake with a healer. The disciplines don't scale DOWN from raid to group mode, so it shouldn't create problems for all classes. Interchangeable tanks work like a charm, but none gains an advantage using spellbooks either.<br><br>If knights are gaining too much of a foothold in warrior tanking power, then you need to shave off some of the fat: NO mana regen gear, no focus effects, no rez/corpse summoning(though insignificant these might be). You are not a SPECIALIZED CASTER, so you don't need this anymore. Downtime going to be part of your disadvantage as a tank wannabe. Stepping on your parent classes toes is not allowed. That should go for all hybrids.<br><br>If that doesn't suit your taste as a solution, then come and rejoice as the Warrior gains all the tools the OTHER tanks have in order to maintain some desirable options in groups. Doesn't affect raids disciplines ... we still get to be main tank for those bosses, but no tank can argue that they can't group effectively either.
