		<td rowspan=2 bgcolor="#050A0E" width=1><img src="/i/p.gif" height=1 width=1 border=0 alt=""><br></td>
	
		<td colspan=2 class="msg_text_cell" width="100%" valign=top style="text-align: justify; 
		" 
			>
			Heck, its not only not a parse, its not even a correct calculation.  Discipline timers refresh when you activate them, not after they expire.<br><br>So it would be 1-(3*.5+7*.95) = 18.5% 'mitigation'<br><br>As for BB's general post:<br>"13.1% reduction in total melee damage without concidering the many other factors alone is much greater than an average 11.54% reduction in only the DI portion of melee damage."<br><br>The number is wrong, as shown above.<br>Otherwise it doesn't show anything directly comparable in quality to stuns.  If one chooses to ignore any and all benefits from 'burst' but timer-limited abilities (such as situations where .50DI for 3 minutes on one or more mobs may be vastly better than a consistent 13.1% dps reduction on a single mob) and deal in terms of flat averaged DPS, fine.  But if that is the case then Defensive isn't the way to go.<br><br>Evasive is available 38.5% of the time.  Its benefits vary based on mobs accuracy, but in general may offer about a 35% reduction in DPS taken.  With DI damage accounting for roughly half of total damage 5% DI damage reduction is about 2.5% dps reduction.  Avoidance caps make that another 1.5% or so.  Higher softcap and overcap returns add in maybe another 2%. From those factors alone warriors are reducing their damage by roughly 6%.  Thats nearly half of 'stun mitigation' (much more properly termed 'avoidance') just by being there, without using disciplines.  Now toss in Evasive at 35% further reduction and its damage taken goes from 94% (undisced) to 61.1% while under evasive.  That is a total net damage taken of 81.3% from the norm of the non-stunning paladin.  That leaves the stunning paladin at 86.9%.  Yep, thats right... more damage taken by a stunning paladin than the warrior against a single stunnable, and low resist mob.  Numbers are illustrative, but approximately correct, substitute your own if you like.<br><br>If you wish you could complicate this up to your heart's content by adding knight 30s disc, warrior furious, both epic clicks, both OoW BP clicks, added dps vs. added healing, etc.  Doing so of course renders the whole thing sufficiently complex in a way that becomes subjective in applicability to make it moot as an argument where numbers are involved.<br><br>The argument that mitigation for warriors is 'only for themself' while a paladins is for the entire group to justify increased warrior mitigation is rather specious.  Currently the overwhelming majority of damage lands on the tank and their death precipitates the group's.  In most situations where this is not the case the warriors abilities rivals a paladins (sometimes exceeding, sometimes trailing) in preventing these deaths.<br><br>That a warrior actually has to use a discipline to take less damage than a paladin on a succession of single mobs expending considerable mana (over 100/tick for chaining OoW stuns, and therefore unsustainable without at least some downtime), gem refresh induced inability to use other spells,  sometimes problematic KB, and with those stuns subject to resists (ignoring for the moment innate and level caps) fails to produce anything resembling a problem.  If regardless of the abilities spent I am never to take less damage than a warrior, then I want my "nearly" to become more universal as well.  That means no level caps, no immunities, unlimited targets, with a cap on the chance of me being interrupted casting.	
		</td></tr>
